"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:1.2.1\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">1.2.1</span> Sheep pen, sheepfold</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">בָּצְרָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(botsrah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mic2:12\">MIC 2:12</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">גְּדֵרָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(gidroth, gidroth ts’on)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num32:16\">NUM 32:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num32:24\">NUM 32:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Num32:36\">NUM 32:36</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam24:4\">1SA 24:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer49:3\">JER 49:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zeph2:6\">ZEP 2:6</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מִכְלָא</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mikla’, mikl’oth, mikl’oth ts’on)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps50:9\">PSA 50:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps78:70\">PSA 78:70</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hab3:17\">HAB 3:17</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מִשְׁפְּתַיִם, שְׁפַתַּיִם</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mishpthayim, shfatayim)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen49:14\">GEN 49:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg5:16\">JDG 5:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps68:14\">PSA 68:14</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">αὐλή</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(aulē)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John10:1\">JHN 10:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John10:16\">JHN 10:16</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">μάνδρα</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mandra)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt2:26\">JDT 2:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt3:3\">JDT 3:3</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0930_sheepfold.jpg\" alt=\"A stone fence protected sheep at night\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">A stone fence protected sheep at night (© Free Bible Images © David Padfield)</figcaption></figure>The sheep pen was an area enclosed by a stone wall or hedge made of branches and thorns. It had a narrow opening through which the sheep could pass and which could be closed with brush or by the shepherd’s body. Sheep were put in the pen at night to protect them from thieves or wild animals.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>“Sheep pen” must often be rendered “place for the protection of sheep,” “place for sheep with a wall built around it,” or “enclosure for sheep.” In contrast to the next entry (<a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.2.2 Animal pen, stall&lt;REALIA:1.2.2&gt;</a>), this enclosure was built out in the areas where the sheep were grazing, and not near the house. It could often be a temporary structure.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer49:3\">JER 49:3</a> the Hebrew word <em>gderoth</em> is rendered “sheep-pens” by <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Jerusalem Bible (1985)\">NJB</abbr> and “sheepfolds” by <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Jewish Publication Society Version\">NJPSV</abbr>. Others have “walls” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New American Standard Bible\">NASB</abbr>, New Century Version [<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr>]) or “hedges” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>, New Living Translation [<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Living Translation\">NLT</abbr>]). Others, however, prefer a small change in the Hebrew, so that it would mean “covered with gashes” as an expression of mourning. Translations that take this approach render the last half of the fourth line in this verse as “lament, and slash yourselves with whips” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Revised Standard Version (1989)\">NRSV</abbr>) or “and score your bodies with gashes” (Revised English Bible [<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr>]).</p>\n<p>The Hebrew words <em>mishpthayim</em> and <em>shfatayim</em> are translated in different ways. In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen49:14\">GEN 49:14</a><abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr> and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Jewish Publication Society Version\">NJPSV</abbr> have “sheepfolds,” while <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr> says “cattle pens.” These versions believe these words refer to an enclosure for domestic animals. <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr> have “saddlebags,” which is preferred by <em>A Handbook on Genesis</em>, page 1090.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
